<article class="about">
  <a class="back" href="/">← Reading journey</a>

  <h1>About R/W Book Club</h1>

  <p class="lede">
    We've been meeting since April {{ site.founded }}. The "R/W" stands for
    <em>Read / Write</em> — we're a technically minded group, and many of us blog.
    We read, but we also write.
  </p>

  <p>
    Each year we read about eight books together, mostly non-fiction. Members
    take turns picking the next book and hosting the meeting where we discuss it.
    This site is the running ledger of what we've read — scroll the
    <a href="/">reading journey</a> to follow it back to the very first meeting.
  </p>

  <h2>Current members</h2>
  <ul class="member-list">
    {% for m in currentMembers %}
      <li>
        <a href="/members/{{ m.slug }}/">{{ m.name }}</a>
        {% if m.pickedCount %}<span class="pick-count">{{ m.pickedCount }} pick{% if m.pickedCount != 1 %}s{% endif %}</span>{% endif %}
      </li>
    {% endfor %}
  </ul>

  <h2>How this site is built</h2>
  <p>
    Everything we've read lives in a database that the club's assistant, Oliver,
    keeps current — one record per book, meeting, member, and author. A small
    Python pipeline turns that into per-page content, fetches and resizes the
    cover art, and hands the result to
    <a href="https://www.11ty.dev/" rel="external noopener">Eleventy</a>, which
    renders these pages. Oliver rebuilds and publishes the site to GitHub Pages
    whenever the club's record changes.
  </p>
</article>
